1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Making a sensible decision, Black reinforces his e5-pawn. } 3... d6
{ Nowadays this move, called the 'Steinitz Defense', is considered too passive. Black locks in his f8-Bishop and gives White a free hand in the center: }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7
{ The effects of the opening moves have favored White. He has better control of the center and freer piece play. Many games continue thus: }
6. O-O Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Re1
{ Practice has shown that White has the advantage. } 8... O-O *

