Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ Is not to be trifled with, and Black has to play with care. I prefer the second choice for Black: }
3... Nbd7 4. f3 { Once more White winds up for his center push. } 4... c5
{ Black responds with his own counter in the center. } 5. dxc5
{ White could play the defensive   5.e3  , but this negates his strategy of playing for e2-e4. Black would play  5...e6  with a fine game.  Neither would the immediate   5.e4  cxd4  6.Qxd4  e5!  work, when Black has seized the center and has the better position. }
5... e6 { Black prepares to recapture the c5-pawn. } 6. e4
{ White completes his plan but at a cost. Black's counter in the center has been quite timely. }
6... Bxc5 7. exd5
{ White has won a pawn but his position is weakened on the g1-a7 diagonal. By continuing: }
7... Qb6 { Black has the superior position. } *

