{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted  (QGA)  follows White's plan of knocking Black's d5-pawn out of the center. Play begins }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ After  2...dxc4  , White can play  3.Qa4+  , immediately recapturing the c4-pawn. But this action causes a premature development of White's Queen. }
3. e3
{ It is better for White to try to recapture the c4-pawn with the f1-Bishop. This is the simplest move.  A key alternative is   3.e4  . Expanding upon the same idea, White gains a larger share of the center. The problem with this is that Black is also quick to react in the center:  3...e5  attacks the d4-pawn. After  4.Nf3  it is a mistake to try to win the e5-pawn with   4.dxe5?  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  Nc6  , when Black gets a good position  exd4  5.Nxd4  Nf6  , Black has an even game. }
3... Nf6
{ In the QGA, Black usually allows White to recapture the c4-pawn. He hopes that he too will attack the center with his own ...c7-c5 to reestablish the equilibrium. }
4. Bxc4
{ White has accomplished his goal: The d5-pawn has been removed and he has gained a lead in development. Play usually proceeds: }
4... e6 5. Nf3 c5 6. O-O
{ The main position of the QGA. White has a lead in development, which gives him an advantage. Black aims to equalize by trading pawns on the d4-square.   The QGA is an excellent defense for those players who like to counterattack. Its drawback is that if White plays accurately, he will keep an advantage for a long while. }
*

