[White "4: Classical Queen Pawn Openings"]
[Black "Tarrasch Defense "]
[Result "*"]

{ For those players who don't like to gambit pawns as Black, the Tarrasch Defense, }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 { is the natural reaction, and after } 4. cxd5 exd5
{ White has tried a large number of moves here:     5.e4!?  dxe4  6.d5  is the Marshall Gambit. Leave it to Frank Marshall to find gambits for both White and Black. White is playing for fast development and this gambit is a dangerous one for the second player.  White can force Black to sacrifice a pawn by   5.dxc5?!  d4!  6.Na4  . This is the Tarrasch Gambit, and after the theoretical recommendation  6...b5  7.cxb6  axb6  , the poorly placed a4-Knight gives Black an excellent position.  The most common moves are   5.Nf3  Nc6  . Black reinforces the pressure on the d4-pawn.  6.--  White can now try   6.e3  Nf6  7.Bb5  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bd7  , which is slightly better for White.  Or he can play the popular fianchetto variation, called the 'Schlechter Variation':   6.g3  Nf6  7.Bg2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Bg5  . Modern practice has shown an advantage for White due to the pressure that White's pieces have in the center. From Tarrasch's view as a classical player, he was certain that Black had achieved an equal game. The Tarrasch Defense was a favorite of Garry Kasparov during his early career. }
5. -- *

[Event "?"]
