{ The 'Neo-Orthodox Defense' begins } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7
5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 h6
{ This puts the question to White's Bishop: Will he exchange Bishop for Knight or move away? @@StartBracket@@The reason for the strange name, 'neo,' is that while Black is playing an Orthodox Defense, the idea of inserting the move ...h7-h6 is relatively modern.   Classical players didn't like weakening their Kingside.@@EndBracket@@ }
7. Bh4 b6
{ Following the usual retreat, Black decides to fianchetto his c8-Bishop as in the Closed Catalan. This variation is called the 'Tartakover, Makogonov, Bondarevsky Variation'. A mouthful you say? That's why its also called the TMB Variation.   I discuss this position and its strategies extensively in 'Winning Chess Brilliancies' @@StartBracket@@Microsoft Press, 1995@@EndBracket@@, on pages 2-15. In this game @@StartBracket@@Robert James Fischer versus Boris Spassky, Reykjavik 1972, Game 6@@EndBracket@@, Black retains a solid central position. }
