{ As an alternative to the Levenfish Attack, White can take a more restrained approach: }
6. Be2 Bg7 7. Be3 Nc6 8. Nb3
{ White's last move distinguishes the 'Nottingham Variation'. White's approach is to keep the d5-square firmly in his sights. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ White intends to keep the center well patrolled by playing f2-f4 and Be2-f3. Black's space deficit encourages him to trade pieces and a common line is: }
9... Be6 { This is possible now that White's d4-Knight has retreated. } 10. f4
Na5
{ Black's point is revealed; he is playing to put a piece on the c4-square:   10...d5  11.f5 }
11. f5 Bc4
{ This final position is known as the 'Byrne Variation'. White has a slight advantage as he tries to stir up trouble on the Kingside. }
