{ The 'Dutch Defense' has a goal similar to that of the Polish Defense. Play begins: }
1. d4 { 1.e4  c5  2.d4  cxd4  3.c3  dxc3  4.Nxc3 } 1... f5
{ Black isn't trying to meet White in the center. Instead, he's trying to stake out his own territory.   It can be argued that the Dutch Defense is a bit more sound than the Polish Defense because Black's opening move at least controls the sweet center. Black wants to continue with ...Ng8-f6 and completely control the e4-square.   White can meet the Dutch Defense with a variety of plans. He can fianchetto his King Bishop as in a Catalan.   Or he can try any of these options: }
2. c4
{ If he likes, White can also play into the main line of the Dutch Defense:   2.e4  Staunton Gambit, If the Dutch Defense sets out to control the e4-square, the 'Staunton Gambit' aims to stop Black's plan in its tracks: White offers his e4-pawn as bait for quick development. Black should accept the gambit  2...fxe4  3.f3  White hopes to induce  3...d5  Black should fall back on his plan of controlling the e4-square   3...exf3  4.Nxf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  with a promising attack.  4.fxe4  dxe4  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Bg5  Bf5  7.Nge2  e6  8.Ng3  Be7  The main line of the Staunton Gambit. Black continues to control the e4-square and has an acceptable game.   2.Bg5  The Dutch Defense is about controlling the e4-square. White can employ another method to stop the grip: White's Bishop move is a favorite of mine. Black has a difficult moment. After  2...Nf6   2...h6  Black's best  3.Bh4  3...g5  %cal Gh4g3,Gf5f4  4.e3  This opens the evil threat of Qd1-h5 Checkmate!  4...Nf6  5.Bg3  Bg7  6.Nd2  White has the advantage. Black's Kingside is extended and the move h2-h4 is sure to undermine Black's position.   2...g6   2...c5  3.d5  Qb6  3.Bxf6  exf6  4.e3  White will play c2-c4 and Nb1-c3 with a sizable advantage. }
2... Nf6 { 2...e6 } 3. Nc3 { 3.g3 } 3... e6 4. Nf3 Be7 { 4...d5  5.Bg5  c6 } 5.
e3 { 5.Bg5  h6  6.Bh4  g5  7.Bg3  f4 } 5... O-O 6. Bd3 d5
{ Black continues his strategy of controlling the e4-square. Black's position is about equal because in this main line, the c1-Bishop has a limited role. Most players like to fianchetto their f1-Bishop as in the Catalan. }
