{ One of the sharpest defenses is the 'Benoni Defense'; it's also one of the most difficult to master. A favorite of former World Champion Mikhail Tal, its success even attracted Bobby Fischer to play it against Boris Spassky in their celebrated 1972 World Chess Championship match. The Benoni leads to extremely lively tactical play that keeps both players on their toes. Play begins: }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 { Black seeks to remove the cramping d5-pawn. } 4.
Nc3 { 4.dxe6  fxe6 } 4... exd5 5. cxd5 d6
{ The starting position of the Benoni Defense. White has been given a central majority. In return, Black has claimed a Queenside majority. Both players will use their majorities to control the other player's pieces. }
6. e4
{ The most dangerous weapon in White's arsenal to try to defeat the Benoni is an immediate 'Pawn Storm Variation'. White immediately expands in the center. One of Black's aims in the Benoni, as in the Benko Gambit, is to fianchetto his f8-Bishop where it might be more active on the long diagonal. Black starts this strategy now.   6.Nf3  Nimzovitch Variation: If the dangers of the Pawn Storm Variation frighten both players, and they should, White can take a more restrained approach by 6.Nf3 White calmly develops his Knight for now.  6...g6  As usual, Black prepares to fianchetto.  7.Nd2  This move distinguishes the 'Nimzovitch Variation'. White aims to plant his Knight on the c4-square, where it will pressure the d6-pawn.  7...Nbd7  Black has also essayed   7...Bg7  8.Nc4  8...O-O  9.Bf4  9...Ne8  which is favorable for White.  10.e3  8.e4  Black intends to meet   8.Nc4  with  8...Nb6  attacking the c4-Knight.  9.Nxb6  Qxb6  8...Bg7  9.Be2  O-O  10.O-O  a6  11.a4  Re8  This shows the most topical of Benoni positions. Both players have safe Kings but the strategies for both sides are enormously complex. Practice has shown that the position is double edged but finely balanced. }
6... g6 7. f4
{ White is planning to blow away the f6-Knight with e4-e5   7.Nf3  Today, the most topical way of meeting the Benoni  7...Bg7  8.h3  White rules out ...Bc8-g4 and any trades. White wants to keep pieces on the board due to the cramping effect of his central pawns  8...O-O  9.Bd3  This modern treatment has had a chilling effect on Benoni players. If allowed, White wants to play O-O and Bc1-f4, with an active game. Black tries to counter with an enterprising gambit:  9...b5  10.Bxb5  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  Qa5+  12.Nfd2   12.Nc3  Bxc3+  13.bxc3  Qxb5  Qxb5  13.Nxd6  The latest word in the modern Benoni theory. The position is a mass of confusion, but for now White has shown a plus in practice.  13...Qa6  14.N2c4 }
7... Bg7 8. Bb5+
{ This is an important intermezzo move. The Pawn Storm Variation has reached a pregnant moment. How will Black handle the check? He has two main choices: White would like to play   8.e5  dxe5  9.fxe5  Nfd7  10.e6  fxe6  11.dxe6  11...Qh4+  12.g3  Bxc3+  13.bxc3  Qe4+  but these tactics don't favor him. }
8... Nfd7
{ Considered the safe choice, the main line runs   8...Nbd7  Best alternative for Black.  9.e5  dxe5  10.fxe5  Nh5  11.e6  11...Qh4+  12.g3  Nxg3  13.hxg3  Qxh1  The tactics of this position are still being debated, with practice favoring White. This is definitely one variation where preparation is a requirement!   8...Bd7  9.Bc4   9.Bd3 }
9. a4 { White is worried about ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 coming with tempo. } 9...
Qh4+ 10. g3 Qe7 11. Nf3 { 11.g4 } 11... O-O
{ This position is considered better for White. } 12. O-O Nf6 *

