[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6: Modern Queen Pawn Defenses"]
[Black "Bogo-lndian Defense "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ After  3.Nf3  , White doesn't allow the Nimzo-Indian. Instead, he invites his opponent to play  3...d5  , transposing back to a classical Queen Pawn Defense.   Or  3...c5  4.d5  , transposing back to a Benoni Defense. Many grandmasters appreciate these transpositions. They feint with a Nimzo-Indian only to transpose to a Benoni. In this way certain lines, such as the Pawn Storm in the Benoni, are averted. }
3... Bb4+
{ If Black doesn't want to transpose back into these defenses, he can give the position its own flavor. This variation is attributed to Efim Bogoljubow.   When faced with a last name like that, it is easy to see why players called this defense the 'Bogo Variation'. Because Black often fianchettos his Queen's Bishop, the defense became known as the 'Bogo-Indian Defense'. If White doesn't want to play }
4. Nc3
{ Transposing back into the Nimzo-Indian, he should block Black's check in one of two ways:   4.Nbd2   Or  4.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@the main line@@EndBracket@@.   Bogo-lndian Defense  4.Nbd2  : My favored continuation is to block Black's check with:  4.Nbd2  My reasoning is simple: I want to play a2-a3 and win the two Bishops as in a classical Nimzo-Indian without spending tempi with my Queen. If Black doesn't give up the two Bishops, my d2-Knight will support e2-e4.  4...b6  This is a key move to understanding the Bogo-lndian. Black tries to control the e4-square with pieces and not by playing ...d7-d5, which requires him to commit himself in the center.  5.a3  Bxd2+  Practically speaking, this capture is forced.  After   5...Be7  6.e4  Bb7  7.Bd3  , White has control over the e4-square and a clear advantage.  6.Qxd2  @@StartBracket@@a paradoxical capture@@EndBracket@@  After   6.Nxd2  Bb7  , White will have to spend time blocking the long diagonal.  After   6.Bxd2  Bb7  , it isn't clear what White should do with his dark-squared Bishop.  6...Bb7  In a few moves, White's plan will be clear:  7.e3  O-O  Black could play   7...Bxf3  8.gxf3  , but White will soon play Bf1-g2 and f3-f4, with a powerful middle game.  8.Be2  d6  9.O-O  Nbd7  10.b4!  The middle game plans for both sides begin to take shape. White intends to fianchetto his dark-squared Bishop for good central control. Black intends to occupy the e4-square with his Knight and follow up with ...f7-f5 to play on the light squares. Practice has favored White.  Bogo-lndian Defense, Main Line: Black's Bishop check has provoked a response and it's certainly natural to rebuff the impudent attacker with an attack of your own:   4.Bd2  This is the main line of the Bogo-lndian, and it's a completely logical counter. If Black is forced to trade Bishops, White's development would get a boost.  4...Qe7  Not wishing to help White develop, Black defends his Bishop.  Black has also tried   4...a5  and   4...c5  , but the text is the most logical.The text position shows White's strategic problem in a different light.What will White do with his f1-Bishop? The c4-pawn means that the f1-a6 diagonal isn't the brightest, so White decides on a fianchetto.  5.g3  It also might seem like a reasonable plan to play for e2-e4. After trading a few pieces with   5.Nc3  Bxc3  6.Bxc3  Ne4  7.Qc2  Nxc3  8.Qxc3  d6  9.e4  Nd7  , Black will play for ...e6-e5 with rough equality.  Nc6  6.Bg2  Bxd2+  Black chooses the right moment to trade Bishops.  After   6...Bxd2+  , White can't play  7.Qxd2?!  Ne4  8.Qc2  Qb4+  , which gives Black the initiative.  7.Nbxd2  d6  This position is typical of the Bogo-Indian. Black has the flexibility to change plans. He now plans ...e6-e5 in order to activate his c8-Bishop.  8.O-O  e5  9.d5  White gains a nice wedge in the center.  9...Nb8  10.e4  This is the starting position for most grandmaster games with the Bogo-Indian. White's central control gives him the advantage, but Black's position is quite solid. Black will play ...Nb8-a6, thereby controlling the c5-square. }
