{ I was so attracted to the Barcza Opening as White that I tried out the same formation as Black against White's Queen Pawn Opening. Known as the 'King's Indian Defense'  (KID)  , this is the favorite defense of both Garry Kasparov and Bobby Fischer. It comes highly recommended! Let's see it in action: }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ Of course, White is under no obligation to occupy the center. He can play much more quietly with his first four moves, but it is these opening moves that put the most pressure upon Black's formation. This serves as the starting position. White has a large number of choices. White's main tries are:     5.Nf3  Main line   5.f4  Four Pawns Attack:   5.f3  Samisch Variation   5.Be2  Averbach Variation }
5. Nf3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8: A Solution to the Queen Pawn Opening"]
[Black "Four Pawns Attack"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f4
{ One of Black's greatest fears in playing the King's Indian Defense is the 'Four Pawns Attack'. White's pawn center is quite imposing! What's worse from Black's perspective, the routine of ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 has been severely disrupted, and it is now impossible for Black to count on this maneuver. A change of plans is needed - and fast. However, don't despair! Although White has occupied the center, his pawns can easily become overextended. }
1... c5
{ Black immediately attacks White's center and forces him to make a decision. }
2. d5
{ White bypasses the c5-pawn. After   2.e5  2...Nfd7   2.dxc5  Qa5  Black threatens ...Nf6xe4, with a winning attack. White has to protect the e4-pawn:   2...dxc5  3.Qxd8+  Kxd8  4.e5  Nfd7  5.Nf3  3.Bd3   3.cxd6  Nxe4  3...Qxc5  reduces a crucial recapture. White is prevented from playing e4-e5 in the future, and play continues:   3...dxc5  4.e5  Nfd7  4.Nf3  O-O  5.Qe2  Bg4  6.Be3  Qa5  7.O-O  7...Na6  Practice has shown the position to be dynamically equal.   7...Nc6  8.h3  Bxf3  9.Rxf3  9...Nd7 }
2... O-O 3. Nf3
{ White must be careful not to overextend his center. A mistake would be   3.e5  Ne8  4.Nf3  Bg4  when White's center collapses under Black's pressure.  5.exd6  Nxd6 }
3... b5
{ Black makes a necessary pawn sacrifice that is similar to the Benko Gambit. Black desperately, and correctly, tries to break up White's center. White must accept the sacrifice because ...b5-b4 threatens to win the e4-pawn. After }
4. cxb5
{ 4.e5  4...dxe5  5.fxe5  Ng4  6.Bf4  b4  7.Ne4  Nd7  Black is well placed to meet White in the center.  8.e6  fxe6  9.dxe6  Rxf4  10.Qd5  10...Rxe4+  11.Qxe4  Nb6 }
4... a6 5. a4 { White decides to cling to his extra pawn. } 5... Nbd7 6. Be2
axb5 7. Bxb5 Ba6
{ Practice has shown that Black has compensation for his pawn. He will try to utilize the half-open b-file to create counterplay. }
8. Bxa6 Rxa6 9. O-O Qa8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8: A Solution to the Queen Pawn Opening"]
[Black "Samisch Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f3
{ Another aggressive system against the KID is the 'Samisch Variation'. In this variation, White's intentions are cleverly disguised. White wants to play Bc1-e3, Qd1-d2, and castle long. He will attack on the Kingside in a style similar to the Yugoslav Attack of the Sicilian Dragon. Because I like to play the Samisch Variation as White, I know that Black has to play carefully to gain a safe position. However, the Samisch Variation has an important drawback. In the words of grandmaster Eduard Gufeld, "Please, ask the g1-Knight how he likes the move f2-f3. He has been robbed of his best square!" }
1... e5
{ This is probably the only time that Black should make this move before castling - an important nuance. After 5...e5 Black is not worried about the ending   1...c6  2.Be3  a6  3.Bd3  b5  4.Nge2  Nbd7  5.O-O  O-O }
2. d5
{ This is considered White's best chance of gaining an advantage. Recall from considering the Barcza Opening that a line like   2.dxe5  dxe5  3.Qxd8+  Kxd8  4.Bg5  4...c6  %cal Gc6d5  5.O-O-O+  Kc7  correctly believing that this middle game is not worse for him.   2.Nge2  %cal Ge8g8,Gb8c6,Gf1e2  2...exd4  3.Nxd4  3...O-O  4.Be2  c6  has Black preparing the break ...d6-d5, with a fine game. }
2... Na6
{ Once again, Black plays for the positional plan of controlling the c5-square. When the colors were reversed, White prefaced this move with a2-a4.   2...c5   2...a5 }
3. Be3 { White sets up the attacking line previously outlined. } 3... Nh5
{ This move has a dual purpose: It clears the way for Black to play ...f7-f5 and possibly ...Qd8-h4+ in order to disrupt White's plan. }
4. Qd2
{ This is one of the most interesting variations of the KID. After 8.Qd2 Black can play   4.g4  Nf4 }
4... Qh4+
{ Or he can try the 'Bronstein Variation'.   4...f5  a key source of counterplay in the KID that gives him a fair game. }
5. Bf2 Qf4 { Black invites White to trade Queens if he'd like. } 6. Be3 Qh4+
{ This invites a repetition, which is declined as follows: } 7. g3 Nxg3 8. Qf2
{ Certainly White must avoid   8.hxg3  Qxh1   8.Bf2  Nxf1  which would result in the loss of a pawn for White.  9.Kxf1  9...Qe7   9...Qh5 }
8... Nxf1 { Now, however, Black is forced to sacrifice his Queen. } 9. Qxh4
Nxe3
{ Black has the threats of ...Ne3-g2+ and ...Ne3-c2+, so White now moves his King: }
10. Ke2 Nxc4
{ Black has a material deficit of two Bishops and two pawns for his Queen. Speaking bluntly, the position is absolutely gross and defies analysis. I've played Black's position against Kasparov and made an easy draw. Players who don't like to sacrifice their Queen should play 8...f5 instead. But please, do yourself the favor of playing out this position against a friend. It will be very rewarding. Play often continues: }
11. b3 Nb6 12. Rc1 Bd7 13. Nh3 O-O 14. Nf2 f6 15. a4 Rae8
{ A fascinating game lies ahead. Clearly, the Samisch Variation is quite a challenging one for Black and he must be on his toes. Averbach Variation: The purpose of f2-f3 in the Samisch Variation is to set up with Bc1-e3 and prevent ...Nf6-g4, which would harass White's Bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8: A Solution to the Queen Pawn Opening"]
[Black "Averbach Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Isn't there another way White can do this without playing f2-f3? With this move, White covers the g4-square and initiates the 'Averbach Variation': }
1. Be2
{ The move is highly transpositional and we haven't reached the Averbach Variation quite yet. }
1... O-O 2. Bg5
{ This is the move that signals the Averbach Variation. White's sixth move is far more annoying than   2.Be3  because on the g5-square, the Bishop is far more active. When Black plays his freeing move ...e7-e5, he will place himself in a nasty pin. }
2... c6
{ Black prepares to counter in the center. The immediate   2...e5  3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8  Rxd8  5.Nd5  would be a failure as Black loses material. }
3. Qd2 e5 { Now this break works because the d5-square is covered. } 4. d5
{ 4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8  Rxd8 } 4... cxd5 5. cxd5
{ While it might be tempting to capture on d5 with the Knight, it is wrong; after playing   5.Nxd5  5...Nc6  6.O-O-O  Be6  Black's Knight goes to the d4-square and Black earns a good game. }
5... Nbd7 6. f3
{ In view of Black's impending pressure on the e4-pawn with ...Nd7-c5, White strengthens his center. }
6... a5 { As before, Black secures the c5-square. } 7. Nh3 Nc5 8. Nf2 a4 9. O-O
Bd7 { Theorists consider the position shown here to be dynamically balanced. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8: A Solution to the Queen Pawn Opening"]
[Black "Mainline vs Kings Indian Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPP3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ By far, White's most popular way of meeting the KID is the main line, where White just develops his Kingside, happy with his central gains: }
1. Nf3 O-O 2. Be2
{ White's last two moves are interchangeable and some grandmasters enjoy the time their opponents spend reflecting about how they intend to meet the Averbach Variation! }
2... e5 3. O-O
{ This is the starting position of the main line King's Indian Defense. My colleague, grandmaster John Nunn, has written two 300-page books called 'The Main Line King's Indian' @@StartBracket@@Henry Holt and Company, 1996@@EndBracket@@ and 'The New Classical King's Indian' @@StartBracket@@International Chess Enterprises, 1997@@EndBracket@@, in which he goes into great detail about the strategic considerations facing both players. Needless to say, it is an impossible act to follow! My recommendation for Black is to play as follows:   3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8  Rxd8  5.Nd5   5.Nxe5   5.Bg5  5...Re8   5...c6  6.Nxe5  Re8  7.Nf3   7.f4  h6  8.Bxf6   8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  gxf4  10.Bxf4  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  Bxe5  Bxf6  9.Nf3  Bxc3+  10.bxc3  Rxe4  Nxe4  6.Nd5  Nxd5  7.cxd5  c6  5...Nxd5  6.cxd5  c6   3.d5  3...Kh8  4.O-O  Ng8 }
3... exd4 { 3...Nc6 } 4. Nxd4 Re8 5. f3
{ 5.Qc2  Nxe4  6.Nxe4  Bxd4   5.Bf3  5...Nbd7 } 5... c6
{ Black is ready to break out with ...d6-d5 or, at certain times, ...Qd8-b6, which can be an annoying move. }
6. Kh1
{ This is the key move in this variation. White has tried other lines, including   6.Nc2  is unable to gain any superiority.  6...Na6   6...a5   6.Be3  One nice trick for Black is and  6...d5  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Nxd5  cxd5  leaving Black with no problems. Instead, White gets off the a7-g1 diagonal where his King might be vulnerable. }
6... Nbd7
{ This is considered the most solid continuation. Black would dearly love to play the immediate ...d6-d5, but it fails:   6...d5  7.cxd5  cxd5  8.Bg5  dxe4  9.Ndb5  White's lead in development gives him the advantage. With the text, Black is prepared to put his Knight on either the e5- or c5-square and, in the cases of ...d6-d5, the Knight can play to the b6-square.  9...exf3  10.Rxf3 }
7. Bg5
{ The f6-Knight is pinned and Black's ability to play ...d6-d5 is slowed. White now has a large choice of alternatives, including   7.Nb3   7.Nc2   7.Rb1  and   7.Bf4  Theory considers the text to be White's best move.   7.Be3  d5  8.cxd5  Nxd5 }
7... h6
{ Black also has his choices,   7...Qb6  and   7...Qa5  have been popular alternatives. I prefer the text for reasons that shall soon be clear: }
8. Bh4 Ne5 9. Qc2
{ One trick that White must avoid is   9.Qd2  Nxe4  because the h4-Bishop is unprotected. }
9... g5 10. Bf2 c5 11. Nb3 Be6
{ Theory considers White's position to be slightly better, but I'm suspicious of this evaluation. Benoni players will be happy to have a powerful e5-Knight, and the b3-Knight is definitely out of play for some time. Black is certainly capable of raising a heck of a fuss. Take a close look at this position and see how much fun playing the KID can be! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9: A Solution to the King Pawn Opening"]
[Black "9. A solution to the King Pawn Opening. The Pirc Defense"]
[Result "*"]

{ %evp 0,4,19,38,92,92,89 } 1. e4
{ After discovering the solidity of building a house in chess, I became attracted to the very same formations against White's King Pawn Opening. This time, however, the ideas were far more tricky for me than in a Barcza Opening and a King's Indian Defense @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@ . In time, I learned to play the 'Pirc Defense', which became a career defense that I still use to this day. The opening move order is quite important for Black as a single mistake can give him a bad game. The opening moves are: }
1... d6
{ Black is heading for the Barcza formation. The alternative   1...Nf6  is the Alekhine Defense, which would provoke e4-e5 - a threat Black will try to avoid.  2.e5  Nd5 }
2. d4
{ White establishes a classical pawn center. White could certainly entertain other, quieter formations, but this is considered White's best. }
2... Nf6 { Black develops while attacking the e4-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ White could also play   3.e5  dxe5  4.dxe5  Qxd1+  5.Kxd1  Ng4   3.f3  g6  4.c4  Bg7  5.Nc3  transposing directly back to the Samisch Variation of the KID. In fact, this was the move order that Kasparov used against me in one of our tournament games. }
3... g6
{ Black initiates the Pirc Defense. Left to his own devices, Black will complete his house and then counter in the center. From this position White has a wide range of possibilities: }
4. f4
{ called the Austrian Attack or the Three Pawns Attack, is the most dangerous for Black. White tries to prevent ...e7-e5 and often plays for e4-e5, booting away the f6-Knight and trying to disturb Black's house.   4.f3  or  4...Bg7  5.Be3   4.Be3  prepares the development of his c1-Bishop so he can castle Queenside and conduct an attack similar to the Yugoslav Attack in the Sicilian Dragon.   4.Bg5  is currently a popular system for White. Aiming for Qd1-d2 and Bg5-h6 to trade dark-squared Bishops, this line is called the Modern System.   4.Be2  launches a credible attacking idea similar to the Averbach Variation in the KID. White plays for h2-h4-h5, trying to blow down Black's house.   4.Nf3  The Main Line, also called The Geller Variation focuses on White's desire to complete his Kingside development and hold a plus in the center. In comparing the starting position, after 3...g6, of the Pirc Defense with that of the KID, the difference is the placement of White's c-pawn. It can be argued that the pawn on the c4-square is far more active and controls the sweet center. On the c2-square, White's Queenside isn't as weakened, so that if White decides to castle there, his King's protection will be significantly improved. The difference comes down to a question of style. One thing is certain: With the pawn on c2, White can use the extra tempo to considerably sharpen the game.  4...Bg7 }
*

