{ Pirc Defense } 1. Be3
{ Building a house is a well-respected defensive strategy in grandmaster circles. For this reason, many players immediately try to storm the foundations by trading off the fianchettoed Bishop. After 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6, Black has committed himself to the fianchetto. The favored move for White to trade the f8-Bishop. White wants to play Qd1-d2, Be3-h6, and probably h2-h4-h5, with a Kingside initiative. In the past, theorists suggested that White should preface the move with 4.f3 thereby preventing a timely ...Nf6-g4. Indeed, f2-f3 forms an important nucleus of White's plans, but this move should be delayed.   1.f3  or  1...Bg7  2.Be3 }
1... c6
{ Black makes an exception to the traditional 'automatic' play to complete his house, not Bg7.   1...Ng4  2.Bg5  h6  3.Bh4  g5  4.Bg3  sends Black on a wild goose chase. He has weakened his Kingside without trading Knight for Bishop. The rule of thumb is that this kind of chase should be encouraged only if Black is able to nab the Bishop. So after 4.Be3 Black must become a little crafty himself.   1...Bg7  The reason for the text is that Black anticipates that White will castle Queenside. He wants to save the tempo ...Bf8-g7 and accelerate a Queenside pawn storm.  2.Qd2  O-O   1...b6  2.f3  Bb7 }
2. Qd2 b5
{ Black reveals his point. He now threatens ...b5-b4, thereby chasing away the c3-Knight, the only defender of the e4-pawn. }
3. f3
{ White reinforces his center. Although the moves 4.Be3 and 4.f3 are interchangeable, both players should be precise with their move order. Under the present order of moves, Black has forced White to include the tempo f2-f3. Without this order of moves, White might have foregone f2-f3 altogether. One of the benefits of f2-f3 is that White can now plan g2-g4-g5, removing an important defender with tempo. Again, Black should resist the temptation to automatically fianchetto his Bishop. }
3... Nbd7 4. O-O-O
{ White has also tried to delay this committed move by   4.Nh3   4.h4   4.Bh6  and   4.g4  amongst others.  aims for g4-g5, after  4...Nb6  Black has made room on the d7-square for his f6-Knight to retreat. That's why Black's opening move order deserves careful scrutiny. }
4... Nb6
{ Both players will zealously attempt to maul one another's King. A sample line might run: }
5. g4 { 5.e5  Nfd5  6.Nxd5  Nxd5 } 5... b4 6. Nb1
{ 6.Nce2  Nc4  7.Qd3  Nxe3  8.Qxe3  Bg7 } 6... a5 7. h4 h5 { 7...Be6 } 8. g5
Nh7 9. Bd3 Bg7
{ This leaves a wild game in view, featuring a typical Pirc middle game. } *

