{ The lines described in the previous section gave a number of grandmasters some clever ideas, including: }
1. Bg5
{ White reasons that he wants to play as before, using Qd1-d2 and Be3-h6 with a nice twist. He can also play for the Austrian Attack with the Bishop on a much more aggressive square. }
1... h6
{ Black puts the question to the Bishop immediately. White would have an advantage after   1...Bg7  2.f4  when the move e4-e5 will come with added punch because the g5-Bishop does so much more than in the previous Austrian Attack variations. }
2. Be3
{ The position shown here is nearly the same as the one shown after 4 Be3 above, with an important nuance: White has induced the move ...h7-h6. The great debate is, which side benefits? It is clear that after the battery Qd1-d2, the h6-pawn is a target and Black's King is stuck in the center. Furthermore, White will be able to play g2-g4, h2-h4 and with g4-g5 insure himself of prying open the Kingside. On the other hand, White has robbed himself of the Be3-h6 trading Bishops option   2.Bxf6  exf6 }
2... c6 { 2...Bg7  3.f3  O-O  4.Qd2  4...Kh7  5.g4 } 3. f3 b5 4. Qd2 Nbd7
{ After these moves, the game is similar to the previous variation with the h6-pawn sticking out. Black's King shouldn't be too uncomfortable in the center because White isn't threatening to crash through any time soon. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9: A Solution to the King Pawn Opening"]
[Black "Pirc Defense with 4.Be2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Be2
{ White has not revealed his point. He might easily transpose into the main line, which I describe later in this chapter. A rather cunning line is: }
1... Bg7 2. h4
{ White has played a belligerent move. It's appalling that White decides to storm the house before the Black King even makes it to the Kingside. White's intentions are as clear as they are aggressive. He will push his h-pawn and rip open the Kingside. After }
2... c5
{ Once more Black strikes in the center with this familiar counter. This brings me to the last wise opening principle of this book: An attack on the wing is best met by a counter in the center. This dictum was laid down centuries ago and it's as valid as ever. Time and time again in master games you will see this type of principled response. Look for it in your games too. Black forces a central response:   2...O-O  for as they say in chess parlance, 'Black would castle into it' And by it, they mean a bone-crunching attack. After White's fifth move, Black should definitely be put off from castling Kingside for awhile.   2...c6   2...h5 }
3. dxc5
{ White could try   3.d5  a6  4.h5   4.a4  e6  leaves White wondering where he will castle  b5  which produces the better position for Black. }
3... Qa5
{ Black utilizes a standard Pirc Defense resource, and threatens ...Nf6xe4 with advantage. }
4. Qd3 { White defends the e4-pawn and sets a cunning trap: } 4... Qxc5
{ 4...Nxe4  5.Qxe4   5.Qb5+  wins a piece.  5...Nc6  6.Qxa5  Nxa5  7.Nxe4  Bxc3+ }
5. Be3 Qa5 6. h5 { White pursues his Kingside play } 6... Nc6 7. h6
{ White achieves nothing from   7.hxg6  hxg6  8.Rxh8+  Bxh8  when Black has a fine position. }
7... Bf8 8. O-O-O Bd7
{ The position has become an unusual Sicilian where Black has an excellent game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
